Advanced Lane Finding Project¶

The goals / steps of this project are the following:

  • Compute the camera calibration matrix and distortion coefficients given a set of chessboard images.
  • Apply a distortion correction to raw images.
  • Use color transforms, gradients, etc., to create a thresholded binary image.
  • Apply a perspective transform to rectify binary image ("birds-eye view").
  • Detect lane pixels and fit to find the lane boundary.
  • Determine the curvature of the lane and vehicle position with respect to center.
  • Warp the detected lane boundaries back onto the original image.
  • Output visual display of the lane boundaries and numerical estimation of lane curvature and vehicle position.

First, I'll compute the camera calibration using chessboard images¶

def sobel_x_thresh(image, sobel_kernel = 3, sobelx_threshold = (0, 255)):

    gray = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    #Take the derivative in x or y given orient = 'x' or 'y'
    sobelx = cv2.Sobel(gray, cv2.CV_64F, 1, 0)
    
    #Take the absolute value of the derivative or gradient
    abs_sobelx = np.absolute(sobelx)
   
    #Scale to 8-bit (0 - 255) then convert to type = np.uint8
    scaled_sobelx = np.uint8(255*abs_sobelx/np.max(abs_sobelx))
    
    Xgrad_binary = np.zeros_like(scaled_sobelx)
   
    # Create a mask of 1's where the scaled gradient magnitude is > thresh_min and < thresh_max
    Xgrad_binary[(scaled_sobelx >= sobelx_threshold[0]) & (scaled_sobelx <= sobelx_threshold[1])] = 1
    return Xgrad_binary

def sobel_y_thresh(image, sobel_kernel = 3, sobely_threshold = (0, 255)):

    gray = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    #Take the derivative in x or y given orient = 'x' or 'y'
    sobely = cv2.Sobel(gray, cv2.CV_64F, 0, 1)
    
    #Take the absolute value of the derivative or gradient
    abs_sobely = np.absolute(sobely)
   
    #Scale to 8-bit (0 - 255) then convert to type = np.uint8
    scaled_sobely = np.uint8(255*abs_sobely/np.max(abs_sobely))
    
    Ygrad_binary = np.zeros_like(scaled_sobely)
   
    # Create a mask of 1's where the scaled gradient magnitude is > thresh_min and < thresh_max
    Ygrad_binary[(scaled_sobely >= sobely_threshold[0]) & (scaled_sobely <= sobely_threshold[1])] = 1
    return Ygrad_binary


def mag_thresh(image, mag_kernel = 3, mag_threshold = (0, 255)):
    
    gray = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    sobelx = cv2.Sobel(gray, cv2.CV_64F, 1, 0, ksize = mag_kernel)
    sobely = cv2.Sobel(gray, cv2.CV_64F, 0, 1, ksize = mag_kernel)
    abs_sobelxy =  np.sqrt(np.square(sobelx) + np.square(sobely))
    
    scaled_sobelxy = np.uint8(255*abs_sobelxy/np.max(abs_sobelxy))
    sxbinary = np.zeros_like(scaled_sobelxy)
    sxbinary[(scaled_sobelxy >= mag_threshold[0]) & (scaled_sobelxy <= mag_threshold[1])] = 1
    mag_binary = sxbinary
    return mag_binary

def dir_thresh(image, dir_kernel = 3, dir_threshold = (0, np.pi/2)):
    
    gray = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    sobelx = cv2.Sobel(gray, cv2.CV_64F, 1, 0, ksize = dir_kernel)
    sobely = cv2.Sobel(gray, cv2.CV_64F, 0, 1, ksize = dir_kernel)
    abs_sobelx = np.absolute(sobelx)
    abs_sobely = np.absolute(sobely)
    
    DirGrad = np.arctan2(abs_sobely, abs_sobelx)
    DirGradBinary = np.zeros_like(DirGrad)
    DirGradBinary[(DirGrad >= dir_threshold[0]) & (DirGrad <= dir_threshold[1])] = 1
    dir_binary = DirGradBinary
    return dir_binary

def R_thresh(image, Rthresh = (200, 255)):
    
    R = image[:,:,0]    
    Rbinary = np.zeros_like(R)
    Rbinary[(R > Rthresh[0]) & (R <= Rthresh[1])] = 1
    return(Rbinary)

def G_thresh(image, Gthresh = (200, 255)):
    
    G = image[:,:,0]    
    Gbinary = np.zeros_like(G)
    Gbinary[(G > Gthresh[0]) & (G <= Gthresh[1])] = 1
    return(Gbinary)
    
def S_thresh(image, Sthresh = (90, 255)):  
    
    hls = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2HLS)
    S = hls[:,:,2]
    Sbinary = np.zeros_like(S)
    Sbinary[(S > Sthresh[0]) & (S <= Sthresh[1])] = 1
    return(Sbinary)

def L_thresh(image, Lthresh = (215, 255)):  
    
    L_channel = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_RGB2LUV)[:,:,0] 
    Lbinary = np.zeros_like(L_channel)
    Lbinary[(L_channel > Lthresh[0]) & (L_channel <= Lthresh[1])] = 1
    return(Lbinary)

def B_thresh(image, Bthresh = (145, 200)):  
    
    B_channel = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_RGB2Lab)[:,:,2]
    Bbinary = np.zeros_like(B_channel)
    Bbinary[(B_channel >= Bthresh[0]) & (B_channel <= Bthresh[1])] = 1
    return(Bbinary)

Region of interest¶

In [3]:
def region_of_interest(image, vertices):
    """
    Applies an image mask.
    
    Only keeps the region of the image defined by the polygon
    formed from `vertices`. The rest of the image is set to black.
    """
    #defining a blank mask to start with
    mask = np.zeros_like(image)   
    
    #defining a 3 channel or 1 channel color to fill the mask with depending on the input image
    if len(image.shape) > 2:
        channel_count = image.shape[2]  # i.e. 3 or 4 depending on your image
        ignore_mask_color = (255,) * channel_count
    else:
        ignore_mask_color = 255
        
    #filling pixels inside the polygon defined by "vertices" with the fill color    
    cv2.fillPoly(mask, vertices, ignore_mask_color)
    
    #returning the image only where mask pixels are nonzero
    masked_image = cv2.bitwise_and(image, mask)
    return masked_image

Implement Sliding Windows and Fit a Polynomial¶

In [27]:
# Define a class to receive the characteristics of each line detection
class Line():
    def __init__(self):
        
        # was the line detected in the last iteration?
        self.found = False  
        #average x values of the fitted line over the last n iterations
        self.left_fitx = None
        self.right_fitx = None
        #polynomial coefficients averaged over the last n iterations
        self.best_leftfit = []
        self.best_rightfit = [] 
        #polynomial coefficients for the most recent fit
        self.current_leftfit = [np.array([False])]
        self.current_rightfit = [np.array([False])] 
        #radius of curvature of the line in some units
        self.radius = 0 
        #distance in meters of vehicle center from the line
        self.line_base_pos = 0 
        # Count the number of frames
        self.count = 0


    def BlindSearch(self,binary_warped, vis = 0):
        
        # Assuming you have created a warped binary image called "binary_warped"
        # Take a histogram of the bottom half of the image
        histogram = np.sum(binary_warped[binary_warped.shape[0]//2:,:], axis=0)
        # Create an output image to draw on and  visualize the result
        out_img = np.dstack((binary_warped, binary_warped, binary_warped))*255
        # Find the peak of the left and right halves of the histogram
        # These will be the starting point for the left and right lines
        midpoint = np.int(histogram.shape[0]//2)
        leftx_base = np.argmax(histogram[:midpoint])
        rightx_base = np.argmax(histogram[midpoint:]) + midpoint

        # Choose the number of sliding windows
        nwindows = 9
        # Set height of windows
        window_height = np.int(binary_warped.shape[0]//nwindows)
        # Identify the x and y positions of all nonzero pixels in the image
        nonzero = binary_warped.nonzero()
        nonzeroy = np.array(nonzero[0])
        nonzerox = np.array(nonzero[1])
        # Current positions to be updated for each window
        leftx_current = leftx_base
        rightx_current = rightx_base
        # Set the width of the windows +/- margin
        margin = 100
        # Set minimum number of pixels found to recenter window
        minpix = 50
        # Create empty lists to receive left and right lane pixel indices
        left_lane_inds = []
        right_lane_inds = []

        # Step through the windows one by one
        for window in range(nwindows):
            # Identify window boundaries in x and y (and right and left)
            win_y_low = binary_warped.shape[0] - (window + 1) * window_height
            win_y_high = binary_warped.shape[0] - window * window_height
            win_xleft_low = leftx_current - margin
            win_xleft_high = leftx_current + margin
            win_xright_low = rightx_current - margin
            win_xright_high = rightx_current + margin
            # Draw the windows on the visualization image
            cv2.rectangle(out_img,(win_xleft_low,win_y_low),(win_xleft_high,win_y_high),
            (0,255,0), 2) 
            cv2.rectangle(out_img,(win_xright_low,win_y_low),(win_xright_high,win_y_high),
            (0,255,0), 2) 
            # Identify the nonzero pixels in x and y within the window
            good_left_inds = ((nonzeroy >= win_y_low) & (nonzeroy < win_y_high) & 
            (nonzerox >= win_xleft_low) &  (nonzerox < win_xleft_high)).nonzero()[0]
            good_right_inds = ((nonzeroy >= win_y_low) & (nonzeroy < win_y_high) & 
            (nonzerox >= win_xright_low) &  (nonzerox < win_xright_high)).nonzero()[0]
            # Append these indices to the lists
            left_lane_inds.append(good_left_inds)
            right_lane_inds.append(good_right_inds)
            # If you found > minpix pixels, recenter next window on their mean position
            if len(good_left_inds) > minpix:
                leftx_current = np.int(np.mean(nonzerox[good_left_inds]))
            if len(good_right_inds) > minpix:        
                rightx_current = np.int(np.mean(nonzerox[good_right_inds]))

        # Concatenate the arrays of indices
        left_lane_inds = np.concatenate(left_lane_inds)
        right_lane_inds = np.concatenate(right_lane_inds)

        # Extract left and right line pixel positions
        leftx = nonzerox[left_lane_inds]
        lefty = nonzeroy[left_lane_inds] 
        rightx = nonzerox[right_lane_inds]
        righty = nonzeroy[right_lane_inds] 

        # Fit a second order polynomial to each
        left_fit = np.polyfit(lefty, leftx, 2)
        right_fit = np.polyfit(righty, rightx, 2)
        
        ploty = np.linspace(0, binary_warped.shape[0]-1, binary_warped.shape[0] )
        left_fitx = left_fit[0]*ploty**2 + left_fit[1]*ploty + left_fit[2]
        right_fitx = right_fit[0]*ploty**2 + right_fit[1]*ploty + right_fit[2]
        
        if np.sum(left_fitx) == 0 or np.sum(right_fitx) == 0 : 
            self.found = False # If no lane pixels were detected then perform blind search
        else:
            self.found = True
        
        if vis == 1:  # to visualize
            ploty = np.linspace(0, binary_warped.shape[0]-1, binary_warped.shape[0] )
            out_img[nonzeroy[left_lane_inds], nonzerox[left_lane_inds]] = [255, 0, 0]
            out_img[nonzeroy[right_lane_inds], nonzerox[right_lane_inds]] = [0, 0, 255]
            plt.imshow(out_img) 
            plt.plot(left_fitx, ploty, color='yellow')
            plt.plot(right_fitx, ploty, color='yellow')
            plt.xlim(0, 1280)
            plt.ylim(720, 0)
            plt.imsave("../output_images/VisualizeLane.jpg", out_img)

        return left_fit, right_fit, self.found
    
    
    
    def FoundSearch(self,binary_warped, vis = 0):
        
        nonzero = binary_warped.nonzero()
        nonzeroy = np.array(nonzero[0])
        nonzerox = np.array(nonzero[1])
        margin = 100
        left_lane_inds = ((nonzerox > (self.best_leftfit[0]*(nonzeroy**2) + self.best_leftfit[1]*nonzeroy + 
        self.best_leftfit[2] - margin)) & (nonzerox < (self.best_leftfit[0]*(nonzeroy**2) + 
        self.best_leftfit[1]*nonzeroy + self.best_leftfit[2] + margin))) 

        right_lane_inds = ((nonzerox > (self.best_rightfit[0]*(nonzeroy**2) + self.best_rightfit[1]*nonzeroy + 
        self.best_rightfit[2] - margin)) & (nonzerox < (self.best_rightfit[0]*(nonzeroy**2) + 
        self.best_rightfit[1]*nonzeroy + self.best_rightfit[2] + margin)))  

        # Again, extract left and right line pixel positions
        leftx = nonzerox[left_lane_inds]
        lefty = nonzeroy[left_lane_inds] 
        rightx = nonzerox[right_lane_inds]
        righty = nonzeroy[right_lane_inds]
        # Fit a second order polynomial to each
        left_fit = np.polyfit(lefty, leftx, 2)
        right_fit = np.polyfit(righty, rightx, 2)
        
        ploty = np.linspace(0, binary_warped.shape[0]-1, binary_warped.shape[0] )
        left_fitx = left_fit[0]*ploty**2 + left_fit[1]*ploty + left_fit[2]
        right_fitx = right_fit[0]*ploty**2 + right_fit[1]*ploty + right_fit[2]
        
        if np.sum(left_fitx) == 0 or np.sum(right_fitx) == 0 : 
            self.found = False # If no lane pixels were detected then perform blind search
        else:
            self.found = True
            
        if vis == 1:
            ploty = np.linspace(0, binary_warped.shape[0]-1, binary_warped.shape[0] )
            out_img[nonzeroy[left_lane_inds], nonzerox[left_lane_inds]] = [255, 0, 0]
            out_img[nonzeroy[right_lane_inds], nonzerox[right_lane_inds]] = [0, 0, 255]
            plt.imshow(out_img) 
            plt.plot(left_fitx, ploty, color='yellow')
            plt.plot(right_fitx, ploty, color='yellow')
            plt.xlim(0, 1280)
            plt.ylim(720, 0)
        
        return left_fit, right_fit, self.found
    
    # Define y-value where we want radius of curvature
# I'll choose the maximum y-value, corresponding to the bottom of the image

    def radius_of_curvature(self, left_fit, right_fit, ploty):

        y_eval = np.max(ploty)
        left_curverad = ((1 + (2*left_fit[0]*y_eval + left_fit[1])**2)**1.5) / np.absolute(2*left_fit[0])
        right_curverad = ((1 + (2*right_fit[0]*y_eval + right_fit[1])**2)**1.5) / np.absolute(2*right_fit[0])
        #print(left_curverad, right_curverad)

        # Define conversions in x and y from pixels space to meters
        ym_per_pix = 30/720 # meters per pixel in y dimension
        xm_per_pix = 3.7/700 # meters per pixel in x dimension

        # Fit new polynomials to x,y in world space
        
        left_fitx = left_fit[0]*ploty**2 + left_fit[1]*ploty + left_fit[2]
        right_fitx = right_fit[0]*ploty**2 + right_fit[1]*ploty + right_fit[2]
        
        left_fit_cr = np.polyfit(ploty*ym_per_pix, left_fitx*xm_per_pix, 2)
        right_fit_cr = np.polyfit(ploty*ym_per_pix, right_fitx*xm_per_pix, 2)
        # Calculate the new radii of curvature
        left_curverad = ((1 + (2*left_fit_cr[0]*y_eval*ym_per_pix + left_fit_cr[1])**2)**1.5) / np.absolute(2*left_fit_cr[0])
        right_curverad = ((1 + (2*right_fit_cr[0]*y_eval*ym_per_pix + right_fit_cr[1])**2)**1.5) / np.absolute(2*right_fit_cr[0])
        # Now our radius of curvature is in meters

        #print('Radius of Curvature:',(left_curverad + left_curverad)/2,'m' )
        return (left_curverad + left_curverad)/2

Steps in the pipeline of this project are the following:¶

1.Apply calibration matrix and distortion coefficients (calculated previously) to raw images.
2.Use color transforms, gradients, etc., to create a thresholded binary image.
3.Apply a perspective transform matrix (calculated previously) to rectify binary image ("birds-eye view").
4.Detect lane pixels and fit to find the lane boundary.
5.Determine the curvature of the lane and vehicle position with respect to center.
6.Warp the detected lane boundaries back onto the original image.
7.Output visual display of the lane boundaries and numerical estimation of lane curvature and vehicle position.

# #Global Array.......................
LeftFitArray_0 = np.array([])
LeftFitArray_1 = np.array([])
LeftFitArray_2 = np.array([])
RightFitArray_0 = np.array([])
RightFitArray_1 = np.array([])
RightFitArray_2 = np.array([])

WINDOW_SIZE = 10  # No samples for moving averaging


def pipeline(image):
    
    global LeftFitArray_0
    global LeftFitArray_1
    global LeftFitArray_2
    global RightFitArray_0
    global RightFitArray_1
    global RightFitArray_2
    
    
    #Apply calibration matrix to video file-------------------------------------------------------------------
    TestUndistorted = cv2.undistort(image, mtx, dist, None, mtx)
    
    #Apply Threshold------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    S_img = S_thresh(TestUndistorted, (180, 255))
    B_img = B_thresh(TestUndistorted, (145, 255))
    L_img = L_thresh(TestUndistorted, (215, 255))

    Comb_Thresh = np.zeros_like(B_img)
    Comb_Thresh[(L_img == 1) | (B_img == 1)] = 1
   
    
    #region of interest-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    vertices = np.array([[(500,400),(800,400), (1280,720), (0,720)]], dtype = np.int32)
    Comb_Thresh = region_of_interest(Comb_Thresh, vertices)
    Comb_Thresh_size = (Comb_Thresh.shape[1], Comb_Thresh.shape[0])
    
    #Warp an image using the perspective transform, M_warped----------------------------------------------------
    WarpedTestImg = cv2.warpPerspective(Comb_Thresh, M_warped, Comb_Thresh_size, flags=cv2.INTER_LINEAR)
    
    
    #Sliding Window---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    binary_warped = WarpedTestImg
    if Lane.found == True:
        left_fit, right_fit, Lane.found = Lane.FoundSearch(binary_warped, vis = 0)
    else:
        left_fit, right_fit, Lane.found = Lane.BlindSearch(binary_warped, vis = 0)
    
    Lane.current_leftfit = left_fit
    Lane.current_rightfit = right_fit
    
    #Averaging the Coeff-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    LeftFitArray_0 = np.append(LeftFitArray_0, left_fit[0])
    LeftFitArray_1 = np.append(LeftFitArray_1, left_fit[1])
    LeftFitArray_2 = np.append(LeftFitArray_2, left_fit[2])
    
    LeftFitAvg_0 = np.mean(LeftFitArray_0)
    LeftFitAvg_1 = np.mean(LeftFitArray_1)
    LeftFitAvg_2 = np.mean(LeftFitArray_2)
    
    RightFitArray_0 = np.append(RightFitArray_0, right_fit[0])
    RightFitArray_1 = np.append(RightFitArray_1, right_fit[1])
    RightFitArray_2 = np.append(RightFitArray_2, right_fit[2])
    
    RightFitAvg_0 = np.mean(RightFitArray_0)
    RightFitAvg_1 = np.mean(RightFitArray_1)
    RightFitAvg_2 = np.mean(RightFitArray_2)
    
    Lane.best_leftfit = [LeftFitAvg_0, LeftFitAvg_1, LeftFitAvg_2]
    Lane.best_rightfit = [RightFitAvg_0, RightFitAvg_1, RightFitAvg_2]
    
    if LeftFitArray_0.size == WINDOW_SIZE:
        LeftFitArray_0 = np.delete(LeftFitArray_0,0)
        LeftFitArray_1 = np.delete(LeftFitArray_1,0)
        LeftFitArray_2 = np.delete(LeftFitArray_2,0)
        RightFitArray_0 = np.delete(RightFitArray_0,0)
        RightFitArray_1 = np.delete(RightFitArray_1,0)
        RightFitArray_2 = np.delete(RightFitArray_2,0)
        
        
    #Visualize--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    ploty = np.linspace(0, binary_warped.shape[0]-1, binary_warped.shape[0] )
#     left_fitx = left_fit[0]*ploty**2 + left_fit[1]*ploty + left_fit[2]
#     right_fitx = right_fit[0]*ploty**2 + right_fit[1]*ploty + right_fit[2]
    left_fitx = LeftFitAvg_0*ploty**2 + LeftFitAvg_1*ploty + LeftFitAvg_2
    right_fitx = RightFitAvg_0*ploty**2 + RightFitAvg_1*ploty + RightFitAvg_2
    
    y_max = max(ploty)  # Find the maximum y value
    Xleft_InterceptBottomImg = left_fitx[ploty.argmax()]
    Xright_InterceptBottomImg = right_fitx[ploty.argmax()]
    
    left_fitx_mean = np.mean(left_fitx)
    right_fitx_mean = np.mean(right_fitx)
    
    Lane.left_fitx = left_fitx_mean
    Lane.right_fitx = right_fitx_mean
    
    #Calculate Curvature----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Curvature = Lane.radius_of_curvature(left_fit, right_fit, ploty)
    # Only print the radius of curvature every 3 frames
    if Lane.count % 3 == 0:
        Lane.radius = Curvature
    
    
    # Calculate the vehicle position relative to the center of the lane-----------------------------------------
    position = (Xleft_InterceptBottomImg + Xright_InterceptBottomImg)/2
    Lane.line_base_pos = abs((640 - position)*3.7/480)   # The gap between lanes is 480 pixels 
     
    
    warp_zero = np.zeros_like(binary_warped).astype(np.uint8)
    color_warp = np.dstack((warp_zero, warp_zero, warp_zero))

    # Recast the x and y points into usable format for cv2.fillPoly()
    pts_left = np.array([np.transpose(np.vstack([left_fitx, ploty]))])
    pts_right = np.array([np.flipud(np.transpose(np.vstack([right_fitx, ploty])))])
    pts = np.hstack((pts_left, pts_right))

    # Draw the lane onto the warped blank image
    cv2.fillPoly(color_warp, np.int_([pts]), (0,255, 0))

    # Warp the blank back to original image space using inverse perspective matrix (Minv)
    newwarp = cv2.warpPerspective(color_warp, Minv_warped, (image.shape[1], image.shape[0])) 
    # Combine the result with the original image
    result = cv2.addWeighted(image, 1, newwarp, 0.3, 0)
    

    # Print distance from center on video
    cv2.putText(result, 'Radius of Curvature: {:.2f}m '.format(float(Lane.radius)), (30,30),fontFace = 16, fontScale = 1, color=(255,255,255), thickness = 2)
    if position > 640:
        cv2.putText(result, 'Vehicle Position: {:.2f}m left of center'.format(float(Lane.line_base_pos)), (30,60),fontFace = 16, fontScale = 1, color=(255,255,255), thickness = 2)
    else:
        cv2.putText(result, 'Vehicle Position: {:.2f}m right of center'.format(float(Lane.line_base_pos)), (30,60),fontFace = 16, fontScale = 1, color=(255,255,255), thickness = 2) 
    
    plt.imshow(result)
    
    
    Lane.count += 1
    return result
